I have several DB table column names with underscores (e.g. first_name, last_name, etc.). When writing the model code in PHP, it is normal to write getters/setters using camelization of the column names. However, when I rewrote the model code in Zephir and used the getter/setter shortcuts, the rest of my PHP code that uses the model started crashing. That's when I discovered that Zephir is simply _capitalizing_ the property names to derive the getter/setter method names when shortcuts are used _instead of camelizing_.

For example, if the property name is `first_name` (must match column name for model to work), the getter ends up being called `getFirst_name()` instead of `getFirstName()` which is more conventional. Same with the setter.

The fix is quite simple. In the file

`zephir/Library/CompilerFile.php` do the following:

In function

``` php
_processShorcuts()
```

Inside the switch-case statements for **get** and **set**,

``` php
            switch ($shortcut['name']) {
                case 'get':
                    ....

                case 'set':
                    ....
```

Replace the line 

``` php
'get' . ucfirst($name),
```

with 

``` php
'get' . Utils::camelize($name),
```

and make the same change for 'set'

Below is the code example.
In writing the model code in Zephir, I wrote the following:

``` php
class Customer extends \Phalcon\Mvc\Model
{
    protected first_name {
        set, get
    };
}

```

The corresponding .c file has the following in it:

``` php
ZEPHIR_INIT_CLASS(MyProject_Models_Customer) {

    ZEPHIR_REGISTER_CLASS_EX(MyProject\\Models, Customer, myproject, models_customer, zephir_get_internal_ce(SS("phalcon\\mvc\\model") TSRMLS_CC), myproject_models_customer_method_entry, 0);

    zend_declare_property_null(myproject_models_customer_ce, SL("first_name"), ZEND_ACC_PROTECTED TSRMLS_CC);

    return SUCCESS;
}

PHP_METHOD(MyProject_Models_Customer, setFirst_name) {
    zval *first_name;
    zephir_fetch_params(0, 1, 0, &first_name);
    zephir_update_property_this(this_ptr, SL("first_name"), first_name TSRMLS_CC);
}

PHP_METHOD(MyProject_Models_Customer, getFirst_name) {
    RETURN_MEMBER(this_ptr, "first_name");
}
```

As can be seen, the getter/setter methods created are **setFirst_name** and **getFirst_name**.

Instead, camelization as suggested above would lead to the more conventional **setFirstName** and **getFirstName** method names.

Is this doable?
